'''Alfred Molina''' (born [[May 24]], [[1953]]) is a [[Tony Award]]-nominated British/American<!--- U.S. citizen ---> [[actor]]. He portrayed [[Doctor Octopus]] in ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' and has had key roles in ''[[Not Without My Daughter]]'', ''[[Chocolat (film)|Chocolat]]'', ''[[Frida]]'' and ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]''. 

==Biography==
===Early life===
Molina was born '''Alfredo Molina''' in [[London]]. His father was a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[Communist]] from [[Madrid]] who worked as a waiter and chauffeur, while his mother was an [[Italians|Italian]] housekeeper who also cleaned rooms in a hotel and worked as a cook.<ref>[http://www.broadway.com/gen/Buzz_Story.aspx?ci=544358&pn=2 Alfred Molina, Q&A Interview: Broadway.com Buzz<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/g2/story/0,,1261494,00.html 'I give good foreign' | The Guardian | Guardian Unlimited<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Molina grew up in a "working-class neighborhood" in [[Notting Hill]]<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/03/03/theater.alfred.molina.ap/ CNN.com - The actor you think you know - Mar. 3, 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> that was inhabited by many other immigrant families.<ref>[http://www.hispaniconline.com/magazine/2004/jul_aug/CoverStory/index.html Hispanic Magazine.com - July/August 2004 - Alfred Molina - Cover Story<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He decided to become an actor after seeing ''[[Spartacus]]'' at the age of nine, and attended the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]].<ref>[http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800018903/bio Alfred Molina Biography - Yahoo! Movies<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===Career===
Molina made his film debut with a minor role in the [[1981]] movie ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'', but his big break came with ''[[Letter to Brezhnev]]'' in [[1985]], which he followed up with a starring role in ''[[Prick Up Your Ears]]'' in [[1987]], playing [[Joe Orton]]'s lover [[Kenneth Halliwell]].  

He starred in the first two series of ''[[El C.I.D.]]'' but left to concentrate on his film work. Subsequent films included ''[[Species (film)|Species]]'', ''[[Dudley Do-Right]]'', ''[[Chocolat (film)|Chocolat]]'', ''[[Not Without My Daughter]]'',  and ''[[Enchanted April]]''. He has worked twice with [[Paul Thomas Anderson]], first in ''[[Boogie Nights]]'' and then ''[[Magnolia (film)|Magnolia]]''. In 2002, Molina portrayed the Mexican muralist [[Diego Rivera]] alongside [[Salma Hayek]] in ''[[Frida]]''. In 2003 he played himself alongside Steve Coogan in ''[[Coffee and Cigarettes]]''. In 2006, Molina portrayed [[Touchstone (As You Like It)|Touchstone]] in [[Kenneth Branagh]]'s film version of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[As You Like It]]''.

Molina's stage work has included two major Royal National Theatre productions, [[Tennessee Williams]]' ''The Night of the Iguana'' (as Shannon) and David Mamet's ''Speed the Plow'' (as Fox). In his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut, Molina performed in Yasmina Reza's [[Tony Award for Best Play|Tony Award]]-winning play ''Art'', for which he received a Tony nomination in 1998. In 2004, Molina returned to the stage, starring as Tevye in the Broadway production of ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]''. For his performance he once again received a Tony Award nomination, this time for Best Actor in a Musical.

In 2007, Molina narrated a 17-part original audiobook for [[Audible.com]] called "The Chopin Manuscript". This serialized novel was written by a team of 15 best-selling thriller writers, including Jeffery Deaver, Lee Child, Joseph Finder and Lisa Scottoline.

===Personal life===
Molina has taken U.S. citizenship.<ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Movies/Artists/M/Molina_Alfred/2004/06/27/760319.html CANOE - JAM! Movies - Artists - Molina, Alfred: Alfred Molina set for big-time recognition<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He has been married to actress [[Jill Gascoine]] since 1985. He has a daughter Rachel (born 1980) from a previous relationship, and two stepsons (Adam and Sean), from Jill's first marriage. He is also a grandfather to Alfie (born Nov 2003) and Layla (born May 2006).

